annotation: New to the network of chess and having not played in years I go with the tried and true (and later I find out it was Fischer's favorite) e4.
To my untrained eye this is a curveball.  No doubt intended to set up d5.
I jump into the middle with both feet.
e4 contested and defended.
Prepares for d5 and to do battle for the middle.
Nice looking fortress I've built but will it hold?
A minor explosion to happen in the Battle of Center Squares.
We end up in the opening: French Exchange Variation (C01). For the moment both kings are exposed.
Develop my bishop and make room for coming O-O.
The old pin the knight against the king trick.
Push the Queen to the second rank and harass the king a bit.  Arguably should have developed the bishop to d2 to parry Bxc3.
Now I wish I had my bishop on d2 so as to not to have to double up my pawns.
Not so pretty.
? Queen properly positioned on second rank with two diagonals available.  But should have castled first?
Aiming to complicate her efforts to castle and now own the long a3-f8 diagonal.  As a bonus my rooks now connected.
Maybe a queenside castle...
Pointing my rook at his king and making a claim on the e-file.
Gives PINK a claim on the d-file but king a bit exposed.   We've castled to opposite ends of the board which usually suggests some exciting attacks on the kings no doubt simultaneously.
Guarding g4 from unwanted intrusion.
PINK's king digs in but loses a tempo.
Threatens fork and the heart of black's network.  At this point black's position is cramped and largely immobile. I believe white has a slight lead in development space and position.
Doubles protection of e6.
? Bold move that may only help black loosening up PINK's cramped position and giving up a strong knight.
Black has the upper hand for the moment.  The knight attack seems now ill-timed.

? My fine position has been reversed.  My queen's stuck in a closet and PINK has equal access to the e-file. Black has options: Ne4.  For white Qf3 may have been the better choice making e4 & h5 uninhabitable for black's knight.
? Gives the e-file back to white.  Why not Rhe8?
King goes all the way down the rabbit hole.  Another tempo lost? Looks like Black queen getting ready to engage the enemy.
If he takes my pawns are undoubled and my B advances to c4.
Can't use the e-file so will lift rook via the h-file while preparing for a future pawn assault on white king's defense.
Queen takes aim at b7 e7 and d6.
Storm brewing on the eastern front.  Do I engage and or let it come to me?  After analysis I elect to parry PINK's attack as it comes.
Add's pressure to black's middle. Black's knight's vulnerable on f6.
Threatens undefended pawn on d4 and eventual attack at f2.
It's the beginning of a series of exchanges.
I should get at least a pawn and freeze black's rook because of threatened mate.
A shield?
Aiming to to back the black queen away from white's king while threatening two-pronged attack on king.  Now PINK's rook and knight are pinned to king's defense.
Steals a pawn and opens up a golden opportunity for Be5.
But white is so focused on what he's doing he does not see Be5. Black teals a pawn back - the score is still zero.
Black cleverly gets a pawn and attacks my undefended Bishop.  But we are both missing the obvious:  Be4.
All I can say is I am totally focused on mounting some combination against the king I cannot see Be4.  Lesson learned... scan the table every piece every potential attack every turn!
This is where I wanted to go.  Now my rook threatens w e8.  We exchange rooks and I mate with Queen. But...
I know PINK won't hit my rook first for that would be mate.  If I attack RxR.  At best I can chase the king around the table for he escapes to c7. So I nab a pawn to keep the score even.
My attack has run out of gas for the moment so PINK pressures white.

I decide to give it go and hope for a blunder.  But Qe2 would be interesting.  After an exchange of queens I might beat black to the pawn promotion. Another more provocative option is Qe8 offering my queen to black.  A temptation that will lead to mate for white if indulged.
Instead black kills another pawn.
I hope now to gain black's rook.
A check is always a beautiful way to buy time and reposition your defense.
Now we are between a rock and hard place.  My attack is thwarted and all remaining pieces are locked up in attack and defense.
Seeing no option I go for the queen exchange.
Now to push pawns and stop his.
Black sees the prize and begins the race. Black has what is now a huge one pawn advantage.  Sometimes grabbing a pawn early pays big later.

My best effort to complicate things for black. But all I did was lose a move.  Better to jump to e1 then cut left to block any promotion.  But the black pawns outnumber my own and are further advanced.  A bad combination.
Black may have done better to bring out the king to dislodge my rook and run her rook to the d-file.
Clear the way for my own.
You can see the sweat on white's brow now.
Not far enough this time.  Should have gone to c5 making black's pawn progress difficult while my own raced unimpeded up the sidelines.

This is a game where pawns made the difference (and missed opportunities on my part).  I resigned here but later analysis says I should have a gone a few more moves to sees black's plan.  Who knows with a little help from black I may have salvaged a draw or better.  Certainly my rook is better positioned to defend and block than block's.

Hi everyone!

A lot of players tend to fall to the knight fork but there are also other forks some that can be very easy to miss the humble pawn fork.  In the three games I am about to show you I had the pleasure of executing such a tactical shot.  In this game sadly due to my inexperience at converting a won position I settled for a draw when I should have gone on to win.  Now I have a little more patience.  You can follow this game with the following analysis:-http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=9582247&fb=1&rnd=0.8716252950274858

Gail kicks off with 1. c4. which is the English Opening.
3. ..... b6 - I decided to fianchetto Fou Leblanc on the a8-h1 diagonal.
5. ...... Bb7 - completing the fianchetto.
8. ..... d6 - now you would never believe that a pawn fork will happen in this quiet looking position now would you?
11. 0-0 - both sides tuck their kings away on the kingside.
12. Re1?? - but there is one coming now!
16. f4 - after the tactical stouche Gail finds herself a piece for a pawn light.
17. ...... Be4 - aiming to initiate another trade off to get into a won endgame.
20. ..... Qxa3 - might as well grab that loose pawn on a3.
23. cxd4 - one pair of rooks is traded off.
26. ..... a5 - passed pawns must be pushed.
28. ..... Qa8 - trying to trade queens but Gail is not having any of it.

Here I make the biggest mistake of my chessic career - a bad draw offer!  Nowadays I hope I am a bit more discerning and patient before I hit that offer draw button.  The way to defend yourself against making bad draw offers in advantageous positions is to have a plan to convert these positions - planless play leads to inferior results.  Here is what Coach Ion had to say in his post match pm.  Hello jstevens1! 
I think the way to learn how to convert late-game advantages is to play them out - indeed even play out endings that look drawish if there looks as though there's still play left. You'll flub the odd one into unnecessary draws or losses that happens to everyone (I can think of three or four at least that I've flubbed on GK) but you will bring home the desired result a whole deal more often and your "conversion" rate can only improve with time. 

Now in your game against yakky I don't really like your last move but it doesn't compromise your winning chances much: you ought still to win from the final position. I do wonder though whether you had made up your mind to offer the draw before you played the move or afterwards. 

Anyhow I'm going to take the game from White's last move 1.d5: 

Instead of 1...Nf8 Black could play 1...Nf6 exploiting the pin on the e-pawn to bring the knight to an active square. But it also carries a threat namely 2...Nxd5 3.cxd5 Qxc5 4.Qxc7 Qd4 with attack on the pinned rook and the f-pawn. Black ought to emerge from this 3 pawns to the good but even if you ended up only two ahead (White plays 2.g3 say and you went ahead with the exchange) you would have a near-on winning advantage still (1...Nf6 2.g3 Nxd5!? 3.cxd5 Qxd5 4.Qxc7 Qd4 5.Kf2 [Black would be more than happy with 5.Qc3 Qxc3 with 2 remote passed pawns in a rook ending - an easy win] 5...a4!?). 

Incidentally this looks like an example of a theme in the latest "Novice Nook" thread. Ordinarily White would want to keep the pieces on and so here. The pure Q P and R P endings are all hopeless for White pretty much. This adds another string to your bow: a latent threat to force piece exchanges. 

Of course after 1...Nf6 2.g3 you might not want to give up the knight in this way and that's fair enough. It might not be the best or simplest way to go. Instead you could redeploy the knight 2...Nd7 3...Nc5 and then start probing on the

Interesting! The only reason Black would play this is to get an open file for an attack on White's king. But since he has no pieces developed White needn't worry for a while!

I think developing the kingside is a higher priority. I'm also not convinced this is the best square for the queen.
A little too bold! White should get his king to safety before opening the centre.
Developing a piece with a threat is always good.
9.Qc2 was the only move.
Black should take the pawn. If White recaptures Black wins a piece by ...f5.
The king was safe enough on e1. 12.exd5 cxd5 13.Nb5 wins at least a pawn.
Opening the e-file must be good for White.
Probably better than leaving it on the open file.

Although this game is not the most accurate I have ever played it was very entertaining to play. Annotations with help of Shredder Classic 2.
This basically allows me a French Defense without the shut-in light squared bishop.
The logical follow up to this move would be to castle kingside then play for f4-f5 but White never gets around to this. Shredder recommends Nf3 instead.
Black has already equalized.

Aiming at the weak b-pawn and discouraging the bishop from moving but the computer didn't like this move recommending 9...Nf5 instead. ...Nf5 allows Black to castle more quickly and as it turns out Black's queenside play is much more powerful with the rooks connected.
A weakness has been provoked in the queenside but it is far easier for Black to create this weakness than to exploit it.
Though this move isn't particularly bad 11...Be7 would have been better White is cramped and Black certainly has time to castle.
The fact that this rook is undefended takes away some of the power of the threats...
...as ...Nc2 runs into Rc1.
Pressuring d4 and hoping to tie White's pieces down to this pawn's defense.

The computer recommended 17...f6 for me here. I actually considered this pawn break during the game to try to free up space for my pieces but I wasn't comfortable with the very weak backwards pawn on e6 especially with that file semi-open. Even knowing the computer's recommendation I still would play the move I played. The open c-file is the main battleground of this middlegame and I want to do everything in my power to control it.
Trying to open and then control the b file as well.
Taking this pawn was a risky decision that considerably sharpens the game. In exchange for the pawn White gets control of the b-file and one nasty pin.

The computer says that Black should not have quite enough compensation for the queen and that ...Qb5 would be better but I was not sure I would be able to hold onto the bishop after moves like Rgb1. I do get a rook bishop and a pawn for the queen which is technically considered even material and attempt to set up a fortress.
White correctly probes for kingside weaknesses as Black's pieces are trapped on the queenside and ill-suited to defend against kingside threats.
...Nb4 would have been better.
...Nb4 still should have been played. Black needs to get his pieces out and harassing the queen.
Preparing to move the rook to the h-file. Black needs to act fast unless he wants to get swiftly mated.

White still has the advantage here although his moves are getting harder to find as Black's collection of pieces are suddenly well coordinated. I remembered Fischer's famous "Game of the Century" against Donald Byrne as an example of how Black should act in such a situation.

This is the point where White loses his advantage and where Black gets an advantage that is according to Shredder already winning. White still would have had a significant advantage had he played 36.Ne2.
If White takes the rook he loses the queen to a knight fork.
I should have played 38...Rxf2 with the same basic idea as 36...Rxf3. This time the knight fork is on d3.
I didn't want to move it to h7 as it would be vulnerable to a queen check and I didn't want to move it to h8 as a later Rxh6 could be check.
Black has more than enough material to defend any threats the Queen can make. The queen may be powerful but without support cannot take down an entire army of pieces.
Black's pieces flood in toward the king. There is no time to waste - White is trying a desperate counterattack of his own down the f-file.
This is the end - White will lose his queen.
White could resign here. After Kg1 Black has his choice of winning moves such as Nf3  and Bb6 .
White finally threw in the towel here.

I illustrate this game to emphasise- never give up. 
On move 26  I lost a bishop due to sloppy playing. After that I concentrated on attacking his king by advancing a pawn right up and by getting my queen and 2 rooks over. Sure a player of 1700 rating would have seen through it but for some of us whose rating hovers between 1550 and 1600 will enjoy this game.
(More entertainment than education )

This is the way I play into the Goring Gambit ("semi-Danish") or Scotch Gambit. It offers BL the option to try 3...c5 here which will leave a large hole at d5 to exploit after 4.c3. 
Also possible there is 4.Bc4 which gets complex tho after 4....b5!? 5.Bd5 Nc6 etc. not 5.Bxb5?? or Qa5  wins the Bishop. I usually opt for 4.c3 as being clearer play for WT at least until I get more analysis done on the alternate line.
Unusual for BL though I have seen it before. I am happy to permit him to take on e4 if he wishes. Then after Be2/o-o/Re1 the position should be quite powerful for WT.
Offering BL either pawn on e4 or b2. I also considered 4.c3 or captures of the d4 pawn. But I was in a scrappy mood and wanted to give him as much complications aor pawns as he would eat~!
BL might have done better to continue developing and increasing his threat vs the e-pawn by ...Nc6. Then WT cannot play Bb5 due to Qb4  winning the Bishop unless Nc3 giving up the N instead.

Now WT is completely ready to play. Whereas BL is behind in development & has used more time on the Qxb2 pawn grab. With WT's lead in development overall and his regional superiority of mobile pieces aimed at the center & K-side he is ready to sac vs any opportunity. And will certainly do so if it will put the BL king on the run vs the fully mobilized WT army.
opportunity knocks!

Also strong for WT the simple Re1  . Or to try 11.Qe2  Kd8 12. f7 Nf6 13.Rfe1 
Also I considered just 11.Re1  followed by Kd8 12.Qe2 and especially in blitz such a less forcing line can often be very effective in getting them to overlook the point of it or using much time to find it. While it is fairly obvious there is then Qe8  threatened the defenses require a bit of thought. Still I rejected it since the correct defense seems to be the all too obvious capture 12...Nxf6 which he might make even as a knee jerk that would cost me the pawn without any special gain ...tho still attacking.

1. .......... f5 - the Dutch Defense hits out at the centre and controls e4.  This move is playable but do watch that Fool's Mate diagonal.
5. .......... Bg7 - black continues to develop on the flank.  I am now ready to castle kingside and I do so next move.
7. .......... c6 - white also develops on the flank and castles next move the purpose of this move is to try and negate the white lsb's path to a8 and perhaps prepare d5.
12. ......... f4 - my opponent and I have been following the main line of the database but we go into unchartered waters next move when my opponent plays his queen to b3.

15. .......... In response to the queen move to d3 I bring out my knight to d7.  This knight will move to f8 to make room for my lsb to come out as I am lagging behind a bit in development.  This allows a discovered check but all that happens is that the queens get swapped off.
16. b4 - backs up his c pawn.
19. Nc3 - knight had to backtrack because of the black lsb's threat to the white pawn on a2.
22. Rd6?  - White overreaches himself here with this move.  An aggressive placement for the rook but this will lead to white losing a pawn.
23. ......... Nd7 - first the passer is blockaded.
25 ........ Bxd6 - and is now rounded up and eaten up!

26. ....... h6 - I have a very weak pawn on e4 which is backward and under a bit of strain so is the f pawn so reinforcements are being brought up.  Over the next few moves a plan to liquidate the weak e and f pawns brews up and ebervesces into an astounding tactical melee!
27. Nb2 - threatens to win the e pawn but as in my previous note I have other ideas.
28. ......... Nhf6!! - attacks the white pawn on e4 - hopefully I will be able to exchange it for my own e pawn.  I do and get a lot more than what I bargained for.  Are you ready ............
30. ............. fxg3 - first a little zwizchenzug!
33.  ....... Kf7 - there I hope you have managed to keep up with that special plethora of exchanges.  Now the black king emerges to take part in the endgame which is going to be a long one!
38. ........ Nf5  I now succeed in removing more wood from the board without compromising my pawn structure.
42. Kf2? - loses yet another pawn to a knight fork.
46. Bf3 - this allows the exchange of another pair of pieces without compromising my pawn structure.
51. Bf3 - keeping one set of minor pieces on the board - if you are a pawn down or more in a king and pawn endgame it is a lost endgame (assuming no doubletons or isolanis)

51. ......... Kd6!! - now we get another tactic the knight and the king are both on dark squares white has a lsb.  This king move keeps out the white king.  I call this tactic the Joblock - it is very effective here.

54. .......... Ke5 - over the last few moves I decided to liquidate my queenside pawns to get my king over to the kingside and try and crown one or both of my kingside pawns.  It will be the g pawn that will spell checkmate for my opponent.  My a pawn is a handy decoy for the white king forcing him to waste 2 vital tempi in capturing the pawn.  Thankfully this decision paid off.
57. Bc8 - defends the h pawn but the knight will soon round it up and eat it up.

60 . Kc5 - the white king is approaching fast?  Will he get to g1 on time?  I now guard the queening square with Nf2 which will force white to give up his bishop.  Notice that I cannot lose this game with the fall of the h pawn whatever happens now.
64. ........ h2 - prevents the wk from reaching g1.
67. ........... Nf2 - the knight moves and forces Kf1 - it is white's only legal move.  Must be careful must not allow the wrong kind of mate!

68. ....... Kh2 - my king feels bad about giving up his beloved steed but soon he is about to get a new wife (not sure it is a good thing - marriages were not always made in heaven in medieval times!!).  It was midnight on Sunday 18 May 2008.  I set my alarm clock for 645 am BST and at the same time set up 69 ......... g4 as a conditional move just in case white takes the knight.

70. Kf1 then resigns - my alarm clock goes off I log in at about 645 BST on Monday morning.  I am greeted by a white flag from my opponent as he cannot stop the g pawn from crowning and then proceeding to play a deadly game of kiss chase with the white king!   Wheeew what a relief!!
The French Defence.
Nc3 is the Paulsen Variation. Other main lines are exd5 (the Exchange Variation) e5 (the Advance) and Nd2 (the Tarrasch).
Other main lines are Bb4 (the Winawer) and dxe4 (Rubinstein's).
The Burn Variation. Steinitz preferred e5 here.
Another option is Ne4 the Tartakower.
The Alekhine Attack.
0-0 here (Spielmann) is actually a good continuation though not as popular as the other 2 lines c5 and Bxg5.
f5 is certainly better here.
c5 is a classical move in the French against white's centre.

A strange looking move merely inviting c4 and forcing the bishop to retreat.
But the target remains the same: Bxh7!

How can black neutralise the threat? 
9. ... g6? is no good as 10.h5 Kg8 11.hxg6 fxg6 12.Rxh7! Kxh7 13.Qh5  Kg7 14.Qxg6  Kh8 15.Qh7 checkmate.
Black could try h6 or f5 (as mentioned earlier).
!! Can you see why it should work in this situation?

This is the only move black can play.
If 10. ... Kxh7 11.Bxe7 Qc7 12.Bd6! and now black must play 12. ... Qxd6 otherwise it's game over. For example: 12. ... Qb6 13.Qh5  Kh8 14.Ng5 and Qh7 checkmate cannot be prevented. 

The queen could also go on a suicide mission but to no avail: 10. ... Kxh7 11.Bxe7 Qxe7? 12.Qh5  Kg8 13.Ng5 Qxg5 14.hxg5 and once more Qh7 checkmate is inevitable (supported by the rook this time).

Look at this position! Black's entire queenside is undeveloped and his King is naked and alone in the other corner. And that is the point of Bxh7 and the question: when does it work? Without the analysis potential of a chess engine it is impossible to calculate with precision the long-term benefits of playing Bxh7 and even computers sometimes cannot see the full potential until a few moves have been made. 
Basically any sacrifice made to open up the opponent's king should be made if (a) the king will end up truly exposed and (b) pieces can be brought into the attack quicker than those brought in to help the defence.
The key move! It opens the h-file for white's rook.

Not 12. ... gxh5 Qxh5  13.Kg7 Qh7 checkmate. 
Another possibility is 12. ... Bxg5 which I played through as the following wonderful King-hunt: 13.hxg6  Kg7 14.Rh7  Kxg6 15.Qh5  Kf5 16.g4  Kf4 17.Qh2  Kxg4 18.Qh3  Kf4 19.Ne2  Ke4 20.Qg4  Bf4 21.Ng3 checkmate and what a beautiful end to an artistic hunt. Never forget that chess is as much art as it is science.

Bringing another piece into the attack. All things considered though 13.hxg6  is a simpler and more obvious move and also possibly guarantees a quicker end to the game: 13.hxg6  Kg7 14.Rh7 ! (which I didn't see at the time) and if 14. ... Kxg6 15.Qh5  Kf5 16.Nxd4 checkmate... very pretty.
And with the h-file open the King-hunt begins.
Kg7 is followed by 15.Rh7  Kg8 16.Qh5 Qf6 17.Ng4 e5 18.Nxf6  Bxf6 19.Rh8 ! Bxh8 20.Qh7 checkmate.

And my opponent resigned.
Comments and questions are most welcome.

Up to this point it has all been played before (Trunov-Gorbunov Donskoj 2003) but White should now continue with his development by playing 0-0.
0-0 may be slightly better.
Having sacrificed a pawn you need to be more forceful: 14...f5 was best.
The wrong plan from White. He should castle and then fianchetto the bishop.
I still like ...f5.
A poor move. Castling was the first priority. Also by putting all his pawns on white squares he leaves himself weak on the black squares.
Giving White an awkward problem - good!
White still has the advantage because of his extra pawn. In addition Black's remaining queenside pawns are isolated and therefore weak.
Protecting the e-pawn with gain of tempo - good!

At this point Black needs to make a plan. Should he try to win back the pawn? Should he try to exploit White's king position? Should he try to exploit White's queen position? How can he make use of the two semi-open files? Can he make constructive use of the two weak pawns?
The first priority is to develop the rook on f8. 19...Rb5 is okay if Black's plan is to double rooks.
Chasing the queen around doesn't really achieve anything. 20...f5 looks good at first glance but after 21.Qc4 Black is in some difficulty. 20...Rd8 or 20...Rb8 is best.
21...Nxd3  is playable and leads to a draw by perpetual check.

A bad move. Rooks shouldn't be used to defend pawns. There was nothing wrong with the simple 22.f3. In fact the pawn doesn't need defending straight away - 22.Qc4 improves the position of the queen whilst also attacking the rook. An alternative was to play Rhf1 not to defend the pawn but to support its advance.
Not as good as it looks because White can answer with 23.d4. Developing the rook on f8 is still the best move.
Allowing Black to regain his pawn.
The only satisfactory answer to the threat of mate.
25...Qg6 may have given Black a better chance of winning the game.
The rook should occupy one of the open files. 26...Rd5 can be followed up by ...Rfd8. The rooks must work in tandem.
Now this isn't so good because it allows White a fork.
The rook is no better here than it was on f8.
White needs to get rid of that powerful knight and this appears to be the only way.
Rook endings are notoriously difficult to win so it might have been better to keep the knights on.
White's best plan was to pressurize the weak pawn on c7 with Rc1 and Rfc3.
Better late than never!
Kd3 must be better.
If we could take the rooks off it's an easy win for Black but with them still on the board it's probably a draw.

I don't know why he didn't just play a5.

50...Rh8 51.a7 Ra8 wins.
Now Black can only draw.
This loses. ...Rh8 was again the best move.

(game info on previous page) Bird's opening (A03) named after the 19th century English master Henry Bird probably just comes outside the bracket of the most popular opening moves: e4 d4 c4 Nf3 and g3.  They all try and contribute to control of the Centre (Nf3 and g2 in a more hyper-modern way) but Bird is less popular than The English (c4) because it weakens WT's King-Side and WT has to watch that fools mate diagonal (e1-h4).  Bent Larsen however used it to good effect.

Nf6 is a better home.  The short and sweet reason is that it protects/attacks more central squares.  Your lack of force in the center is going to hurt later on.
I think a better position here would have been to b5 and prepare to fianchetto this bishop.   That would have put you on the long white diagonal pointing straight for my castled king.
b6 b5 or c5 would have probably been better at the moment.  The pawn swarm in front of this knight is going to cause him some trouble.
Ne7 was what you were looking for here....
...because your knight is now lost...
....with your only compensation being a pawn.
I think it was too early to advance your queen at this point.  I think  e5 would have worked better to break the pawn chain and get your other bishop and knight into the mix.

It's difficult to remember sometimes but the # of pieces I have pointing at a4 out numbers yours so the pawn will just get lost in the exchange and then your b pawn will closely follow.  with those two passed pawns I think Ra6 was in order before pushing this pawn that way you could get your king's rook over to a8 and you would have had some real power on the queens side of my board.
again I think the e pawn was the one to push.  h6 didn't serve you much purpose.
always be wary of revealed attacks.  it would have been better to save your rook and try to fight off the pawn promotion.
